      "died_year": 1909,
      "bio": "Alfred Cleaver (b. c. 1834; d. 27 August 1909) was from a lace-making family. By 1862 he was in partnership with his brother Francis Frederick Cleaver. They ran a lace dressing, dyeing and bleaching works on Wilford Road under the name of FF and A Cleaver and Co. Other partners in the business included Henry Massey Bishop (until 1865) and William Mayo (until 1870). The partnership between Francis Frederick and Alfred Cleaver was dissolved on 15 March 1881. Alfred Cleaver and Co. carried on business as lace dressers, lace dyers and bleachers and finishers at Lenton. Richard Landor Warham left his partnership with Cleaver in this firm on 30 June 1895.\n\nAlfred Cleaver contributed to the 2nd Report of the Children's Employment Commission, 1862, commenting that a limitation of the hours for workers under 18 would make no difference if applied across the trade, and that if the hours were limited at night he would begin at 6 and find no difficulty.\n\nHe married Annie Bennett (1838–1869) in 1863. Their only son was Robert Clifton Cleaver (b. 1868; d. 1 October 1900, Brandon, Manitoba, Canada). Alfred then married Mary Adelaide Allen (1841–1901) in 1874.",
